<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Failure Blamed on Georgian Position </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502223094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1625 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502223094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS correspondent Vadim Byrkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 25 Feb -- The third round of talks to settle 
the Abkhazia-Georgia conflict, sponsored by the UN and SCSE and 
with Russia as mediator, ended today in Geneva without the 
signing of a final document. ITAR-TASS was told by the press 
service of the plenipotentiary representative of the Republic of 
Abkhazia in Moscow that the talks dealt with peace guarantees in 
the region, return of refugees, and Abkhazia's political status. 
  The Abkhazian side put the failure to sign a final document 
down to the Georgian delegation's "uncompromising position" over 
a political status for Abkhazia. According to the press 
service, this status amounts in essence to the relationship of 
imperial center and colony, a lack of desire to accept current 
realities. This toughening of the Georgian government's stance 
is attributed by Abkhazia to "the signing of a treaty with 
Russia and hopes that Russian troops will police Abkhazia, and 
also an attempt by certain circles in the West to preserve the 
Shevardnadze regime". 
  Despite the difficult nature of the talks, it was decided to 
continue the search for a political solution to the 
Abkhazia-Georgia conflict. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

