<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Decision Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2502190794 Kiev KIEVSKIYE VEDOMOSTI in Russian 23 Feb 94 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> WS2502190794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev KIEVSKIYE VEDOMOSTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Comments by Volodymyr Malynkovych, political expert; </F>
Mykhaylo Horyn, leader of the Ukrainian Republican Party; and 
Oleksandr Moroz, chairman of the Socialist Party of Ukraine 
Political Council, on the decision of Ukrainian President Leonid 
Kravchuk not to run for president; place and date not given] 
  [Text] [Volodymyr Malynkovych] Leonid Kravchuk is 
apparently very tired. 
  The situation in the country is catastrophic, and he 
understands that if nothing changes it will even deteriorate. 
Additionally, his ratings have been declining recently. 
  He would most probably lose the elections. To resign means 
to at least save face. I believe that his decision is serious. 
  [Mykhaylo Horyn] Leonid Kravchuk understands that a new 
stage of the building of the Ukrainian state has begun, which 
requires that definitely new tactics be worked out. A new 
president is needed for new tactics. 
  [Oleksandr Moroz] Leonid Makarovych [Kravchuk] has not yet 
officially announced that he will not run for president. If he 
decides to do so, this will be a politically correct act. The 
popularity of Leonid Kravchuk is decreasing. He and [Supreme 
Soviet Chairman] Ivan Plyushch are responsible for the failures 
of the Supreme Council. The refusal to participate in the 
elections is a political defeat, but participation in the 
elections would be an even bigger one for him, because he does 
not have any chances. 

</TEXT>

