<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Observers Visit Dniester, Meet With Smirnov </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2602204894 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1800 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2602204894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Anca Florea report from Chisinau] </F>
  [Text] A group of 40 international observers representing 
the Council of Europe and the CSCE, in the Republic of Moldova 
to monitor the early parliamentary elections, visited Tiraspol 
today. The group of observers, of which nine are Romanian 
parliamentarians, met with Igor Smirnov, president of the 
self-proclaimed Dniester Republic. 
  To begin with, Smirnov presented a brief report on the 
socioeconomic conditions in the area, after which he answered 
questions asked by the observers. 
  Among the issues discussed were Dniester citizenship, which, 
I would like to point out, the separatist authorities attempt to 
force on the residents on the left bank of the Dniester River, 
and the use of the Romanian language as a state language; in 
this connection, I have to remind you of the pressure to which 
the three Romanian schools in Dniester are subjected -- in the 
past weeks they have been obliged to return to the Cyrillic 
alphabet. And, of course, the main thing, the Ilascu case. 
  From the international observers we learned that Igor 
Smirnov 
said that Ilascu is, quote, a bandit, unquote, a terrorist about 
whom our state's laws have made a decision and no one may 
interfere or disregard the people's will. He also affirmed that 
due to contradictions between the legislation of the Republic of 
Moldova and that of the so-called Dniester Republic, Ilie 
Ilascu's possible election to the Parliament of the Republic of 
Moldova will not be respected. 
  According to the same sources, Igor Smirnov's attitude 
toward 
the observers representing the CSCE and the Council of Europe 
was one of detachment and indifference. 
  Also today, the same group of observers visited polling 
station No. 1 in Varnita, which is located on the right side of 
the Dniester River, where from 21 February to this afternoon at 
1600 more than 2,000 residents from the other bank, the left 
bank of the Dniester River, had cast their vote. 

</TEXT>

