<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   First Multiparty Elections Begin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702070794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0607 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2702070794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valery Demidetsky] </F>
  [Text] Chisinau February 27 TASS -- The first-ever 
parliamentary elections on a multi-party basis are being held in 
Moldova today. Twenty independent candidates and 1,022 
candidates from 13 parties and blocs contend for 104 seats in a 
new parliament. 
  Numerous public opinion polls taken on the eve of the 
elections forecast a convincing victory of the Agrarian 
Democratic Party headed by Parliament Speaker Petr Lucinschi. 
  Sociologists' view is that success is also expected to be 
achieved by the Socialist, Social Democratic, and Republican 
Parties, which, like the Agrarians, strive for Moldova's 
independence, a fair solution to the Gagauz and Dniester region 
problems, and for stronger ties with the Commonwealth of 
Independent States. 
  They will be opposed by movements which believe that Moldova 
must unite with Romania. Those movements have a following 
despite the unpopularity of such slogans in Moldova. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

