<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Early Returns `Sensational' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802093294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0640 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802093294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Chisinau, February 28 TASS -- The early returns of 
the parliamentary elections in Moldova have proved sensational. 
Spot calculation of the ballots has shown that the despite 
forecasts, the coalition of the Socialist Party and 
International Movement Unity, mainly backed by the 
Russian-speaking population, are in the lead in Chisinau, some 
cities and rural districts of the republic. 
  Together with the Agrarian Democratic Party headed by 
parliament speaker Petr Luchinschi, the socialists are ahead of 
all the other parties. 
  Judging by the preliminary results, the opposition in the 
new 
parliament will be made up of pro-Romanian coalition of 
intellectuals and peasants and the Christian Democratic Popular 
Front, which rank third and fourth but will be unable to for a 
majority in new parliament. 
  The above four parties cleared the four-per cent election 
hurdle and won seats in the new parliament. 
  If the forecasts based on the preliminary returns 
materialise, the Agrarian Party will have to team up with the 
socialists to form a majority in the parliament and form a new 
government to lead the republic out of the crisis. If this does 
not happen, "Moldova is in for difficult times", according to 
Petr Luchinschi. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

