<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Duma Amesty Decision Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further Duma Council Comments </H4>
<F P=102> LD2802144194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1345 
GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802144194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 28 Feb -- The State Duma Council sees no 
grounds for thinking that the State Duma exceeded its powers and 
violated the law and the consitution with its decision on the 
amnesty. That was the conclusion reached by the participants in 
today's session of the chamber's council. 
  The council discussed the situation that has developed over 
the anmesty decision and the negative reaction to it from the 
president's staff. 
  Commenting on the course of the session at the request of 
the 
ITAR-TASS correspondent, Valentin Kovalev, deputy chairman of 
the Duma, said: "Several of the country's political figures have 
spoken in the press about the amnesty and stated that the act 
adopted by the State Duma should be regarded more as a pardon 
than as an amnesty." However, "there are clear legal criteria 
that make it possible to distinguish between these two acts. An 
amnesty is a legislative instrument that is binding for all. A 
pardon is an act that is applied individually and must be 
applied strictly to a specified person. Furthermore, a pardon 
covers only the convicted. An amnesty also covers those under 
investigation, as in this case." 
  "In my view, there are no grounds whatsoever for saying that 
the State Duma exceeded its rights and violated the law and the 
constitution; the Duma Council registered this opinion in the 
record, and there were no objections to this view," Valentin 
Kovalev noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-14796 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov039_b_94007" </HT>


