<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Duma Amesty Decision Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Barannikov Welcomes Amnesty </H4>
<F P=102> LD2502213694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1941 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502213694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS corespondent Olga Solodova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 25 TASS -- Former Russian Security 
Minister Viktor Barannikov, who was arrested as an organiser of 
the armed opposition revolt last October in Moscow, welcomed the 
amnesty to anti-Yeltsin rebels proclaimed by the State Duma, but 
does not believe himself to be guilty of anything. 
  "I welcome the amnesty if it leads to stabilisation of the 
political situation in the country", Barannikov was quoted as 
saying by his lawyer Dmitriy Matveyenko on Friday. 
  Matveyenko, however, told TASS that the former minister 
understands that an amnesty covers only guilty people and "does 
not consider himself to be such a man". 
  Barannikov is currently staying at home. He was transferred 
from prison to hospital because of heart problems and later 
released on condition that he stays in moscow. 
  The lawyer said his client had been already discharged from 
hospital and his state of health is satisfactory. 

</TEXT>

