<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Duma Amesty Decision Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Gorbachev Says Decision Premature </H4>
<F P=102> LD2502161094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1402 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502161094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Former president of the USSR Mikhail Grobachev 
believes that the State Duma's resolution on political amnesty 
was discussed with President Boris Yeltsin beforehand. In an 
interview with Interfax on Friday he noted that the speaker of 
the parliament's lower chamber Ivan Rybkin insisted on taking 
this decision, and, in Gorbachev's opinion, "this decision is 
too serious not to have been discussed with the president 
beforehand." 
  Gorbachev says that the fact that in his speech to the 
Federal Assembly on the following day Yeltsin did not mention 
the subject of amnesty confirms his version. 
  Gorbachev pointed out that he had always favored that the 
coup plotters face a trial, a trial which would be open and 
complete, "otherwise we will not learn the lessons of the August 
1991 events." 
  At the same time, he said, if the State Duma's resolution 
really promotes national accord, he is ready to understand and 
accept that. 
  Gorbachev noted that he is ready to support the decision if 
the State Duma, all political movements of the country and 
Russian society will act jointly for the sake of accord, for the 
rescue of Russia, as it was declared after the adoption of the 
amnesty resolution. 
  "Even though all this concerns me directly, because the 
creation of the State of Emergency Committee inflicted a 
unrepairable damage to the country and to me personally, I put 
the interests of Russia higher," he stressed. 
  However, Gorbachev did not rule out that the State Duma's 
decision would finally lead to further confrontation. (The full 
text of the interview given by M. Gorbachev to Interfax will be 
published in one of the next editions of "Interfax-Exclusive"). 

</TEXT>

