<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Duma Amesty Decision Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Democratic Russia Denounces Decision </H4>
<F P=102> LD2602191594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1818 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2602191594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Coordinating Council of the "Democratic Russia" 
Movement has called the Duma's amnesty decision "an attempt of 
revenge by communist and fascist extremists." 
  The move threatens all Russia since "it can undermine 
political stability and disturb peace in Russia," says a 
statement released by the movement in Moscow on Saturday. 
  The movement regards the decision as legally misleading 
since 
amnesty as pardon presupposes reference to concrete criminal 
code clauses. However, there are no such references in the 
ruling, which need to be reexamined by the Prosecutor General 
from the angle of its compliance with the law. 
  Those Duma members and factions that voted for the amnesty, 
as democrats believe, cannot expect popular trust today, nor can 
they hope for respect by posterity. "This applies most of all 
to those of them who just recently disguised themselves as 
democrats, above all Sergey Shakhray and Sergey Stankevich, the 
Russian Unity and Concord Party leaders. On February 23, 1994, 
they deserved the name "traitor," the document says. 
  The democrats are convinced that at a time of rampant crime 
and political instability, putting the Duma's amnesty into 
effect "threatens the rights, life, and property of the people 
of Russia and the constitutional system in the country; it will 
untie the hands of both those who once rebelled against the 
legitimate government and of a significant number of criminals." 

</TEXT>

