<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Duma Amesty Decision Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Chubays: Amnesty Absolves `Murderers' </H4>
<F P=102> LD2502174794 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1547 GMT 
25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502174794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A media briefing took place in Moscow today. 
Anatoliy Borisovich Chubays, chairman of the State Committee 
for Management of State Property, spoke at it. The majority of 
his talk was devoted to the plans for privatization and Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin's message to the Federal Assembly. You 
can hear the second part of Anatoliy Borisovich's news 
conference tomorrow. But now we shall tell you about, we shall 
dwell on, the other no less important and urgent questions which 
Anataoliy Chubays touched upon. 
  [Begin Chubays recording] A few words about the Duma's 
amnesty decision. Overall I must say that this decision of 
course qualitatively alters the situation, in the sense that the 
Duma and its leader, Rybkin, have revealed their true colors, 
and have called a spade a spade. Everything can now be seen in 
its true light. Any illusions which existed before on this 
matter have now been dispelled. Everyone should be clear about 
this. 
  To tell the truth, I am concerned not only about Khasbulatov 
and Rutskoy, personally -- good luck to them. What I am worried 
about is that the decision in the form in which it has been 
adopted, this decision essentially saves actual murderers -- and 
I use these words advisedly -- actual murderers from any 
punishment at all. There is, for example, a certain 
Shtukaturov who, it was established during an investigation, 
personally fired a grenade launcher at Ostankino. Four people 
died as a result of that shot, including one video engineering 
and three cloakroom assistants. 
  Totally innocent people died. Their blood is on the hands of 
the murderers. Since the moment the amnesty decision was made, 
the blood is also on the hands of those who voted for it. 
Zhirinovskiy personally, and Zyuganov personally, have blood on 
their hands and so have their groupings. 
  I would like to ask Zhirinovskiy personally, and Zyuganov 
personally, to go and meet the families of the people who died 
-- if only the families of the cloakroom attendants and the 
video engineer -- and to explain their actions and how they can 
justify their decision. What they will have is not an abstract 
vote in the Duma but a conversation with living people, the 
relatives of those who died at the hands of murderers who will 
be at liberty tomorrow, and who did not use cold steel -- a 
knife or a pistol -- but fired a grenade launcher in the capital 
in broad daylight on a Sunday. This man is to be freed tomorrow 
thanks to the decision of the State Duma. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

