<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Duma Amesty Decision Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Lysenko: Amnesty `Destabilizing Factor' </H4>
<F P=102> LD2602192394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1818 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2602192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The State Duma deputy Vladimir Lysenko, one of the 
leadership of the Yabloko faction, does not believe that there 
will be civil reconciliation in Russia after adoption of the 
memorandum on accord and resolution on amnesty by the State 
Duma. On Saturday in his interview with Interfax he expressed 
opinion that people "who are in Matrosskaya Tishina and 
Lefortovo will start an active political struggle against the 
president, government, and existing regime immediately after 
their liberation." 
  Lysenko qualified the resolution on amnesty, which, as he 
said, was initiated by the leader of the Party of Russian Unity 
and Concord Sergey Shakhray, as "a destabilizing factor." At 
the same time he pointed out that if "an extremist wave is not 
very high after the liberation of the October events 
participants then Shakhray will bypass his major political 
rivals of democratic orientation, Yegor Gaydar and Grigory 
Yavlinskiy." "If the situation sharpens then the consequences 
will be very serious both for Shakhray and for the Party of 
Russian Unity and Concord headed by him. In this case the 
president will dismiss the initiator of this document," he said. 
  Lysenko did not rule out possibility of "preliminary 
contacts" between the State Duma speaker Ivan Rybkin and Boris 
Yeltsin on the issue on amnesty. At the same time he declared 
that "Shakhray was the first in this issue." "I am almost sure 
that first of all Shakhray has coordinated this issue with 
Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin," said Lysenko. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

