<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Duma Amesty Decision Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Rybkin Says Consultations Needed </H4>
<F P=102> LD2602192794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1916 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2602192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksandr Chernov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 26 TASS -- Russian State Duma 
Speaker Ivan Rybkin told ITAR-TASS today they will have to take 
up the amnesty question several times, as the process will last 
for six months and require explanations as need be. 
  Rybkin said they need most interaction with the president, 
the government and the Federation Council. The interaction has 
been discussed with Presidential Assistant Georgiy Satarov. 
There is also need for a memorandum to include a system of 
criteria and a mechanism to ensure national reconciliation, 
civil peace and accord. 
  Speaking of possible consequences of the amnesty, Rybkin 
said 
"street political fighting and gladiators a la Rus are 
inadmissible. If someone tries to do it, one can be sure: the 
State Duma and the president will be able to put them in place." 
  The speaker also reminded that "amnesty as a rule suggests 
toughened punishment for repeated violation". 
  As for persons liable for political amnesty, they are 
expected to "actively join Russian life and the search for 
interaction". Those who do not want to involve in "the common 
cause" should better say at home, said Rybkin. 

</TEXT>

