<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Duma Amesty Decision Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   People's Party Urges Court Inquiry </H4>
<F P=102> LD2702155994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1426 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2702155994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Russian People's Party led by Telman Gdlyan has 
urged President Boris Yeltsin to ask the Constitutional Court to 
question the legitimacy of the State Duma resolution concerning 
amnesty. 
  In its statement published Saturday evening the party 
qualifies the resolution on granting amnesty to those who 
"instigated and joined" the events of August 19-21, 1991, May 1 
and September 21-October 4, 1993 as "another victory won by the 
anti-reformist forces and disregard for the norms of morality 
and law". According to the document, connivance at these forces 
was what inspired them to stage their revolt in August of 1991, 
which led to frustrating the plans to sign a union treaty, 
breaking up the USSR and exposing the nation to severe 
hardships. "Unfortunately, as a result of political 
near-sightedness, the Russian leadership continued Gorbachev's 
policy of conciliation with the reactionary forces," the 
document states. 
  According to its authors, the State Duma resolution, "which 
is allegedly aimed at reaching conciliation and national 
concord, is in fact an attempt to legitimize lawlessness, 
anarchy and the use of force in political strife". 
  The Russian People's Party expressed concern over the fact 
that the encouragement of those who organized and perpetrated 
"monstrous crimes" may lead to another coup "aimed at curbing 
democratic reforms and unleashing a civil war". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

