<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Duma Amesty Decision Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Popov Accuses Yeltsin of `Inaction' </H4>
<F P=102> LD2702154594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1426 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2702154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A well-known reformist Russian politician has 
described the position of President Boris Yeltsin and his team 
on the recent amnesty issue as one of "amazing inaction." 
  Gavriil Popov, chairman of the Russian Movement for 
Democratic Reforms, addressing a meeting of the movement 
leadership on Saturday, said the president could have 
forestalled the amnesty decision of parliament by putting before 
it his own draft resolution laying down conditions on which 
those involved in last October's conservative revolt could be 
released, one of which could be a ban on any political activity 
for a specified period. 
  Parliament's amnesty resolution could prove to be "either a 
step towards national conciliation or a step towards the 
aggravation of the situation," Popov said. 
  He said the prosecution of the organizers of the 1991 coup 
attempt and of the October 1993 rebellion had proved "the total 
helplessness" of Russia's law enforcement system. The 
Prosecutor General's Office needs "purging from top to bottom," 
he said. 
  At the same meeting, Popov described NATO's plan to carry 
out 
air strikes against the Bosnian Serbs as "the first attempt of 
the West to provide a legal basis for Russia's expulsion from 
the number of great powers." 
  He said the fact that the case of the Ames couple, charged 
with espionage for Russia, was given publicity at a time when 
the Serbs were withdrawing their heavy weapons from around 
Sarajevo looked like "an attempt to discredit in the eyes of the 
Americans the first independent step of Russia." 
  "Surely America could not admit that its policy in 
Yugoslavia 
had fallen through," Popov said. 

</TEXT>

