<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Duma Amesty Decision Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Legal Status of Decision Analyzed </H4>
<F P=102> MK2602094094 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 26 Feb 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> MK2602094094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Amnesty: ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI Experts' </F>
Opinion"] 
  [Text] Russian General Prosecutor Aleksey Kazannik must 
apparently have contradictory feelings about having landed in 
the problematic legal situation created by a majority of the 
State Duma deputies who spoke for passing the decree announcing 
political and economic amnesty. 
  First, being general prosecutor, Aleksey Kazannik has no 
right to oversee the legality of a legal act passed by the State 
Duma. Hence his unequivocal statement that the General 
Prosecutor's Office would immediately execute the Duma decree as 
soon as the document is on the general prosecutor's desk. As 
many people know, a package of Duma acts was delivered on the 
evening of 24 February at 15a Pushkinskaya Street, where A. 
Kazannik's agency is located. He, according to General 
Prosecutor's Office officials, is ill at the moment. Will this 
circumstance affect the date for making a decision? 
  Second, there is also no knowing what the general 
prosecutor's reaction would be to the circumstance that a number 
of noted lawyers have serious doubts about the constitutionality 
of some of the provisions of the amnesty decree. Solving such 
differences is the prerogative of the Constitutional Court, but 
it is not functioning at present. 
  What shall be done in this case? How is one to qualify the 
Duma decree in regard to acts of treason? -- precisely this 
article is invoked to charge a number of persons from among the 
organizers of the August 1991 and October 1993 events. Would it 
not be acting against logic and legal norms if the Duma 
amnesties Rutskoy, Khasbulatov, and others, and leaves in jail 
those who fall under more merciful articles of the Criminal Code? 
  Finally, one detail of no mean importance is the entering 
into force of the decree as soon as it becomes published. The 
State Duma has no press organ of its own that could be an 
official information source. The Duma is not known to have 
passed any normative act on this score. This means that the 
appearance of Duma decisions on the pages of some newspaper is 
no more than information. 
  Thus, in addition to creating political tensions, the State 
Duma decision also creates a field for confrontation of a legal 
nature. 
  Time will tell whether the legal community is going to have 
an impact on the Duma decision. At any rate, the controversial 
nature of this situation will affect the future of the Lefortovo 
inmates. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

