<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Prisoners To Seek Stability </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702153394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1426 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2702153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The leader of the National Salvation Front and 
former MP, Ilya Konstantinov, has said that "the former inmates 
of Lefortovo, as well as most political forces in the country 
and State Duma deputies, are not interested in bringing 
political strife in Russia beyond legitimacy; they intend to 
work to stabilize the political situation". 
  An active participant in last May's and last October's riots 
in Moscow, Konstantinov left the Lefortovo prison as a result of 
the amnesty proclaimed by the State Duma on February 23rd. 
  According to Konstantinov, the amnesty granted to "those who 
defended the Supreme Soviet and the Constitution is first of all 
an act of justice", since "the people charged together with him 
are not to blame for anything". 
  Konstantinov described the attempts to link the amnesty with 
the start of another spiral of civil war in Russia as "political 
provocation". According to him, in Russian society there are 
forces interested in "inciting political hysteria" with a view 
to using the resulting situation as a means of pressure on the 
State Duma and on the opposition. 
  When asked about his short-term plans, Konstantinov said 
that 
he intends to "have a rest and get his bearings". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

