<H3> <TI>   Gaydar, Gorbachev Comment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702202594 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1900 GMT 
27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2702202594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [Passage omitted] [Announcer] The State Duma has 
decided on a political amnesty. The resolution was published on 
25 February, and on the 26th, Aleksandr Rutskoy, Ruslan 
Khasbulatov, Albert Makashov, Viktor Anpilov, Ilya Konstantinov 
and others emerged from detention. [passage omitted] 
  Yegor Gaydar, of Russia's Choice, was one of the few who 
voted against the political amnesty. 
  [Begin Gaydar recording] I am absolutely convinced, no 
shadow 
of doubt, that this decision is a step towards destabilizing the 
situation in Russia. I am absolutely convinced that the people 
just released from prison will in the coming months take charge 
again of forming armed gangs who will hit the Moscow streets. I 
am absolutely convinced that their conduct will lead to 
bloodshed. I would like Russia to recognize who are its heroes, 
and who is leading it along this path. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] Now the opinion of those whom we approached for 
their comments. Mikhail Gorbachev is the ex-president of the 
former USSR, the former general secretary of the former CPSU, 
and a witness in the SCSE case. 
  [Begin Gorbachev recording] (?Regarding this decision), I 
feel that the State Duma is of course entitled to make it. That 
is its prerogative, as in the Constitution. So everything is 
clear from the legal standpoint. 
  Secondly, an amnesty is not an acquittal. It is clemency. 
This has to be kept in mind. The main aspect of it is that if 
three-fourths of the deputies equate Russia's current situation 
to one of grave crisis and conclude on the need to abandon all 
that drives us apart, if in this situation such a majority 
decision is reached by deputies, then I am ready to agree with 
them. 
  So in the given situation, I would say this: I agree with 
the decision as understood in my first point. Recriminations 
must not be allowed onto the scene. This is a signal, the 
alarm, that we have to abandon secondary considerations. Given 
that, I am in favor of the State Duma's decision. But if it is a 
move back to the previous strife, recriminations and tension in 
the country, then I condemn those who want to use the State Duma 
in this way to provoke civil conflict. [end recording] [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

