<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poltoranin Warns of Consequences </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702153294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1340 
GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2702153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 27 Feb -- The release of those responsible 
for the October bloodshed in Moscow who have been given an 
amnesty by the State Duma will only assist their return to 
active politics. This opinion was set out in an interview 
Mikhail Poltoranin, member of the "Russia's Choice" faction of 
deputies and chairman of the Committee for Information Policy in 
the State Duma, gave to an ITAR-TASS correspondent. In his 
view, following the release of the "Lefortovo" inmates, "the 
president must not slacken his grip on the reins of power, 
otherwise the carriage of Russian statehood could go off the 
rails." 
  For his part, the former KGB head, Vadim Bakatin, speaking 
from political and professional experience, forecasts that "in 
the present circumstances many of the Lefortovo inmates will 
rush to whip up the crowd to act against the president." If 
events turn out that way, he suggests, the force of the law will 
have to be applied at once to political adventurists. 

</TEXT>

