<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakray Hopes for `Civilized' Struggle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702191494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1758 
GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2702191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 27 Feb -- "The release of Rutskoy will alter 
the configuration of candidates at the coming presidential 
elections, and will especially weaken Vladimir Zhirinovskiy's 
position," deputy of the State Duma, Minister for Affairs of 
Nationalities and Regional Policy Sergey Shakhray said in an 
interview with an ITAR-TASS correspondent today. He voiced the 
hope that those released from Lefortovo "will wage the political 
struggle in civilized forms." 
  "There is in me, as in anyone else, an element of alarm in 
connection with the political statements of the inmates of 
Lefortovo released yesterday," Sergey Shakhray added. "The 
political organizations which achieved only a political amnesty, 
should take upon themselves responsibility for the actions of 
the released leaders. If the latter plan to continue the 
struggle in the elections like other citizens of the Russian 
Federation, that is a normal phenomenon, but if they are 
planning to fight in order with the help of slogans to seize, 
destroy, or gun down -- that means fresh criminal cases will be 
instituted and there will be no consensus or reconciliation." 
  But Deputy Konstantin Zatulin in an interview to ITAR-TASS 
expressed the opinion that any political statements by Ruslan 
Khasbulatov and Viktor Anpilov on leaving Lefortovo are "quite 
natural." The most important thing was whether these statements 
would be followed by any political actions. Konstantin Zatulin 
considers it expedient to "discuss in the Duma the question of a 
possible ban on political activity by active participants in the 
October events of 1993." 
  We remind you that after coming out of Lefortovo Viktor 
Anpilov spoke today on Moscow's Theater Square, calling on 
several hundred activists of "Working Moscow" and the Russian 
Communist Workers' Party to set up a workers' party. 
  In an interview to REUTER's agency Aleksandr Rutskoy's aide 
Andrey Fedorov stated that his boss "will not stay out of 
politics because he has never given up the idea of becoming 
president. He has come out of prison in a fighting mood." 
  As for Ruslan Khasbulatov, he told journalists that he was 
leaving politics and intends shortly to visit his relatives in 
Chechnya. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

