<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kazannik's Stand on Amnesty Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602220394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2129 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2602220394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 27 TASS -- "The strange stand of the 
Russian procurator general's office provokes bewilderment," 
presidential assistants Yuriy Baturin and Georgiy Satarov told 
ITAR-TASS on Saturday. 
  "The Russian procurator general sent a letter to the State 
Duma on Saturday morning to specify circumstances preventing the 
procurator's office from the implementation of the Duma 
resolution on political amnesty. Two Duma committees started to 
prepare a response to the procurator's inquiry believing that 
the procurator general's office waits for the answer," they said. 
  Meanwhile the committees did their work, the procurator 
general's office implemented the resolution to free culprits of 
the October 1993 bloodshed, which runs counter to the law, 
judging by Kazannik's letter. 
  The resolution on liberation of the accused was signed by 
Deputy Procurator General Kartsev "on silent consent of the 
procurator general, stressed presidential assistant on national 
security and doctor of juridical sciences Baturin. As a result, 
the procurator general's office created a precedent of illegal 
implementation of decisions, he said. 
  In his turn, Satarov said the procurator general's office 
adopted a resolution to free the Lefortovo inmates while the 
Duma tried to remove contradictions in its resolution on 
political amnesty. 

</TEXT>

