<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intelligence Boss To Phase Out Spy-Journalists </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK2602093094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 26 Feb 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> MK2602093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Pavel Koltsov report under the "Moscow Rumors" rubric: </F>
"Spies Will No Longer Be `Journalists'? Things Seem To Be 
Moving That Way"] 
  [Text] It has transpired that Yevgeniy Primakov, director 
of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service (FIS) has ordered that 
the financing of foreign offices of a number of Russian 
publications used by FIS officers as journalistic cover be 
stopped. 
  Inside the FIS, however, they see nothing sensational about 
this. Yevgeniy Primakov arrived at the conclusion as early as 
two years ago that the Russian intelligence service had more 
than enough journalist "cover." Chiefs of many Russian mass 
media had long been convinced of that. Thus a decision has been 
made to phase out journalist cover until none remains. In the 
United States, for example, there has long been an act 
prohibiting intelligence officers from working under the guise 
of journalists. 
  In all fairness, far from all professional Russian spies 
subscribe to their superiors' decision. "While journalist 
status is not diplomatic immunity, of course, it is still a 
useful thing," one of them argued. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

