<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poltoranin on Presidential Stand on Mass Media </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602181794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1723 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2602181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 26 TASS -- The first and second TV 
and radio channels must be state, chairman of the State Duma 
committee for Information Policy and Communications Mikhail 
Poltoranin told ITAR-TASS here today. 
  "One should only welcome special attention of the president 
given to the issue in his message to the Federal Assembly. But 
I would not hurry to rejoice as there may be forces to urge the 
president on unjustified decisions," he said. 
  In the words of Poltoranin, he "repulsed the attacks of 
forces wishing to divide the material-technical basis of mass 
media and break the single information space for the past two 
years." 
  His parliamentary committee receives inquiries of deputies 
who are alarmed with the attempts to divide the influence 
spheres in mass media bodies. "The president said that TV and 
radio channels are not liable for privatization and shall be 
state, but one cannot say for sure whether they will remain 
state in future," added Poltoranin. 
  In his words, the parliamentary committee aims to create 
conditions for economic independence of mass media, which "is 
the only guarantee of observation of constitutional rights in 
Russia at a time of anarchy." "If mass media fails to get the 
economic basis for its independence it will be suppressed and 
this process has begun. The president shall say the word in 
order not to allow this to happen," said the committee chairman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

