<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Urged Not To Be `Hypocritical' on Ames Case </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502165294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1504 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature] </F>
  [Text] It is an open secret that Americans spend on 
intelligence, in other words "espionage", much more than all 
other countries of the world taken together. So, the U.S. 
should not be hypocritical, a high-ranking Russian diplomat told 
Interfax on Friday, commenting on the United States' attempts to 
attach special importance to the case of the Ames couple, 
arrested for charges of espionage in favor of Moscow. 
  To quote this diplomat, "if Americans have any queries about 
specific details, representatives of the Russian and American 
special services should discuss them in the spirit of our 
friendly relations." 
  The Foreign Intelligence Service (FIS) has neither confirmed 
nor denied the reports that representatives of the CIA and the 
EIS have met in Moscow to discuss the Ames affair. "We do not 
comment on such information," a representatives of the FIS's 
press bureau told Interfax. 
  He expressed surprise about the hullabaloo raised in the 
U.S. 
in connection with the Ames affair. "We are not doing anything 
in the U.S. that the U.S. is not doing in Russia," he said. 
"Americans are not surprised that their nearest associates -- 
Britain and France -- collect information in the U.S. as well, 
friendship and the secret service are two seperate things," he 
said. 
  He confirmed that Russian competent bodies had collected 
compromising information about American diplomats' and Russian 
citizens' collaboration with the American secret services. He 
gave to understand that "in a certain situation Moscow might 
make use of this material," but expressed hope that things would 
not come to that. 
  Asked about the FIS's possible reaction to the U.S. 
administration's decision to oust the Russian diplomats who 
worked with the Ames couple, he said that this is not the FIS's 
business. Such decisions are taken at a high political level - 
by the president or government - and are implemented through the 
Foreign Ministry. The FIS has nothing to do with this, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-14834 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov039_a_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-039 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Diplomat on Upcoming Meeting in U.S., Ames </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502200094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1843 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502200094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Vanichkin] </F>
  [Text] Washington February 25 TASS -- The U.S. President 
met leaders of the Congress in the White House on Friday. The 
meeting was attended by lawmakers from the Democratic and 
Republican Parties. 
  The White House Press Secretary Dee Dee Myers said that the 
meeting of the U.S. President with congressmen focused on 
providing U.S. aid to Russia. Recently, a number of U.S. 
lawmakers called to freeze U.S. aid or reduce it, following a 
scandal which flared up around the CIA officer Aldrich Ames and 
his wife charged with spying both for Russia and the United 
States. 
  "Undoubtedly, the president intends to oppose any efforts 
aimed at reducing U.S. aid to Russia," Dee Dee Myers said, 
adding that the president is convinced that the politics of the 
U.S. Administration, including its support to Moscow, meets U.S. 
national interests. 
  Dee Dee Myers said that at present, the U.S. and Russia are 
making efforts to settle the problem around the "Ames" case at 
different levels and using different channels. The press 
secretary pointed out that the Russians had not responded to 
U.S. demands so far, adding that they expected a reply in the 
near future. No one of the U.S. administration has mentioned 
yet what demands Washington made on Moscow, motivating their 
silence by the interests of national security. 
  Presumably, one of the channels expected to be used by the 
two sides to resolve their problem is a visit to Washington by 
first Russian Deputy Foreign Minister G. Mamedov. The 
high-ranking Russian diplomat, who arrived in Washington on 
Thursday night, intends to meet U.S. First Deputy Secretary of 
State [title as received] Strobe Talbott and other foreign 
ministry officials on Friday. 
  Mamedov's visit to Washington had been scheduled long ago to 
discuss different problems of international politics. 
Nevertheless, talking to journalists on Friday Mamedov made it 
clear that the "Ames case" would be discussed. "We are concerned 
about anything which might be detrimental to Russo-American 
partnership," Mamedov said. "However, we believe that we have 
accumulated enough confidence and gave sufficient impetus to 
these relations so that we could overcome any problem," he said. 

</TEXT>

