<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chief of Defense Forces Participates in NATO Training </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2502202494 Riga DIENA in Latvian 14 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> WS2502202494 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga DIENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Latvian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Baiba Melnace: "Turlais Returns From NATO </F>
Northern Group Training"] 
  [Excerpt] Riga, 11 Feb -- For the first time, the Baltic 
states, Poland, Russia, and all Scandinavian countries, which 
thus far do not belong to NATO, took part -- on partnership 
rights -- in NATO Northern Group staff training "Viking rewiev 
'94" in Norway. Latvia was represented in this training by the 
Commander of the Latvian Defense Forces, Dainis Turlais. 
  All three commanders from the Baltic states had a separate 
meeting with the chiefs of the Scandinavian Armed Forces. The 
most important was the meeting with the Danish high-level 
military persons, D. Turlais told DIENA. During the talks, a 
decision was made that Latvian officers would begin their 
training with Danish assistance as early as this month. A plan 
was worked out to prepare the Latvian officers for the joint 
Baltic peace battalion. The Scandinavian states have decided to 
create a council with the aim of coordinating military aid for 
the Baltic states. 
  As DIENA was told by Turlais, this year the training had a 
special meaning -- how to create new relations between the 
northern states and the Baltic states in the framework of the 
Partnership for Peace program. The foreign minister of Norway 
made a forecast for the nearest future -- Sweden and Finland 
would join the EC and later would become members of NATO. 
Subsequently, this would show the Baltic states the way to 
integrate in the group of the Scandinavian states and next also 
in NATO. 
  The mayor of St. Petersburg Anatoliy Sobchak Spoke against 
this very sharply and categorically. He described such 
cooperation as a threat to Russia, which absolutely cannot be 
permitted. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

