<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Says Pardon `Presidential Prerogative' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602171894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1652 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2602171894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 26 TASS -- A letter of Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin to State Duma speaker Ivan Rybkin 
reminded him that the pardon is a presidential prerogative under 
the Russian Constitution. The letter was passed over today by 
presidential adviser Georgiy Satarov. 
  The letter says the deputies used the notion of "political 
amnesty" instead of the "pardon" term. Referring to the 
presidential message, Boris Yeltsin also reminded the speaker 
that civil reconciliation does not mean all-forgiveness and 
clemency should not run counter to the law and morals. 
  The president offered deputies of the lower parliament 
chamber to improve the resolution and bring it in correspondence 
with the constitutional norms. Yeltsin also considers it 
necessary to elaborate a criterion of politicians' 
responsibility for their decisions, says the letter. 

</TEXT>

