<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amnesty Suspension `Not Legitimate' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602200594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1818 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2602200594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The demand by the Russian President to "suspend the 
amnesty" declared by the State Duma, is not legitimate, Interfax 
was told Saturday by the chairman of the security committee of 
the Russian State Duma Viktor Ilyukhin (Communist party faction). 
  He believes the resolution of the political and economic 
amnesty is "the right and timely act. It does not flare up a 
civil war. It is those who are trying to stay in power." 
  Ilyukhin said that according to the Russian Constitution 
adopted at the referendum on December 12, the adoption of the 
act on amnesty is the prerogative of the lower house of 
parliament and "the president, and the Federation Council have 
nothing in common with it. [no end quotation mark as received] 
  Speaking about the resignation of the Russian Prosecutor 
General Aleksey Kazannik, Ilyukhin said that he made a premature 
step. "If he really wants to guard legality and order, he must 
not resign but implement the decision of the legislative body." 
  The State Duma, believes Ilyukhin, will confirm the act 
again, since most deputies voted for it. 
  By his actions the Russian President has confirmed again 
that 
he had never respected the old Constitution and will not respect 
the new, presidential Constitution, said Ilyukhin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

