<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Embassy Counselor Ordered To Leave Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802163894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1614 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Andrey Palariya and Vladimir </F>
Smelov] 
  [Text] Moscow, February 28 (TASS) -- CIA agent James Morris 
working as a counselor at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow was 
declared persona non grata on Monday, following the expulsion of 
a Russian diplomat in Washington. 
  A U.S. diplomat was summoned to the Department of North 
America of the Russian Foreign Ministry earlier today to receive 
the following statement: "The Russian Foreign Ministry is 
lodging a protest against illegal activities of the American 
side with regard to an official representative of the Russian 
foreign intelligence service who has been working in Washington 
since the summer of 1993 by mutual consent" of Russia and the 
United States, Ministry spokesman Grigoriy Karasin said. 
  "In this situation, we have to declare, on the basis of 
reciprocity, a CIA officer in Moscow persona non grata and 
demand that he leave the Russian Federation," the statement said. 
  "The Russian Foreign Ministry proceeds from the fact that 
there are special channels for settling issues arising on both 
sides in connection with intelligence or counterintelligence 
activity. These channels can and should be engaged. This will 
allow (us) to find a mutually acceptable way out from the 
current situation and avoid its politicisation," the statement 
said. 
  The U.S. Embassy has been also presented with a diplomatic 
note. 
  ITAR-TASS has learnt that Morris will leave Russia within 
seven days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

