<H3> <TI>   Security Official on Ramifications of Ames Case </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802175794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1649 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802175794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A high-ranking officer of the Russian special 
service stressed that certain circles in the U.S.A. intended to 
make a pause in the bilateral relations due to the case of 
Ameses in order to examine what was happening in Russia. 
[sentence as received] 
  According to the same source, there was definitive pressure 
exercised on U.S. President Bill Clinton and his Aide Strobe 
Talbott in this direction. 
  Commenting on possible response of the U.S. to expulsion of 
U.S. Minister-Counsellor James Morris from Russia, the 
high-ranking officer told Interfax that "escalation was 
undesirable. However, Interfax it is to take place it will be 
bilateral." He said Moscow was unwilling to surrender its 
positions. 
  He also emphasized that, in his opinion, the lay off of the 
Federal Intelligence Service's Director General, Nikolay 
Golushko, had nothing to do with the Ameses. 

</TEXT>

