<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Growing Spy Mania' Seen in U.S. After Ames Case </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802204294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1925 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802204294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service (FIS) has 
started an investigation to conjecture the possible effects of 
the case of the Ames couple, accused of spying for the Soviet 
Union and subsequently Russia, a source close to the FIS said. 
  The source told Interfax on Monday that one of the aims of 
the investigation was to reveal sources of possible information 
leakage from the FIS. 
  "I don't think we have any 'moles' or 'rats' in our service, 
but extra caution will do us no harm," he said. 
  He declined to either confirm or deny that the Ameses had 
been Soviet and Russian intelligence agents. 
  "The investigation has nothing to do with the apprehensions 
that somebody penetrated our intelligence files and found the 
Ameses there," the source said. 
  He said the West was bound to make the most of the Ames case 
to disorganize Russian intelligence and its networks abroad. He 
also said the CIA and other Western intelligence services are 
paying closer attention to Russia, and that there exists "a 
growing spy mania in the United States, comparable to that of 
the Cold War times." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-14857 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov040_a_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-040 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

