<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry `Implicitly' Approves NATO Action in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2802180794 Paris AFP in English 1759 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2802180794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, Feb 28 (AFP) -- Russia implicitly approved 
the downing of four Bosnian Serb aircraft by NATO warplanes 
Monday, saying whoever flew over Bosnia in violation of a UN 
vote carried the full responsibility for what happened. 
  The comment came in a Foreign Ministry statement after 
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic arrived here Monday for 
talks with Russian officials hours after NATO aircraft shot down 
four military planes believed to belong to the Bosnian Serb 
forces. 
  "Whatever party (Serb, Moslem or Croat) flew over Bosnia in 
violation of United Nations Security Council resolutions, it 
must carry the full responsibility for what happened," the 
statement said. 
  The Ministry said it continued to analyse the situation, 
implying that the downing could be criticized at a later date. 
  A high-ranking Russian diplomat earlier told the INTERFAX 
news agency that the Ministry had asked the UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) in Bosnia to explain the shooting down of the four 
Galeb planes by US F-16 fighter jets in a pre-dawn strike Monday. 
  He added that if UNPROFOR information proves to be true, 
"the 
Bosnian Serbs have violated one of the UN Security Council 
resolutions banning any miltary flights over Bosnia-Herzegovina." 
  The resolution, adopted last year and backed by Russia, has 
repeatedly been violated by Bosnia's three warring factions -- 
Serbs, Moslems and Croats, the diplomat said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

