<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Says `Much To Be Clarified' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802192194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1910 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow February 28 TASS--There is much to be 
clarified about the incident with four planes which bombed the 
town of Travnik in central Bosnia and were brought down by NATO 
air forces, which exercised control over the no-fly zone in the 
air space of Bosnia and Herzegovina, Vitaliy Churkin, deputy 
Russian foreign minister, said on Monday evening. 
  According to him, "It is not clear so far, what sort of 
planes were shot down". 
  As soon as the first report about the incident was received, 
the Russian Foreign Ministry got in touch with the Serbian 
leadership, he told a press conference held in connection with a 
visit of a delegation of NATO officials to Moscow. 
  The Serbian leaders were "utterly bewildered" as they could 
not understand, why the Serbian planes should bomb Travnik, the 
site of Croat-Moslem clashes, Churkin said. 
  "Whatever party should have made the military air raid in 
Bosnia in violation of the relevant resolutions of the UN 
Security Council on the no-fly zone, it bears the full measure 
of responsibility for what has happened," he said. Military 
planes of the belligerents must not fly over Bosnia, he 
emphasized. 
  "If all the reported circumstances should be corroborated, 
it 
will be evident that the regime of the no-fly zone established 
by a resolution of the UN Security Council was violated--with 
all the resultant consequences. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

