<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Churkin Comment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802205094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1925 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802205094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At a press conference in Moscow tonight, Russian 
Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin described the 
consultations between the Russian Foreign Ministry and NATO 
experts as the first working event making Russia's joining 
"Partnership for Peace" possible. 
  According to Churkin, the meeting withdrew all remaining 
ambiguities and questions as to Russia's joining "Partnership 
for Peace." "The question was how to make the best use of the 
cooperation with the North Atlantic alliance envisioned by the 
program," Churkin was quoted as saying. Today Russia sees no 
ambiguities and obstacles for the program to function at a 
larger scale, Churkin added. 
  The deputy minister said it was necessary to sign a 
framework 
document and agree on specific areas of cooperation for Russia 
to join "Partnership for Peace." "Now Russia needs to decide who 
and when will sign the framework document," the Russian 
diplomat said. 
  Commenting on the combat jets shot down this morning, 
Churkin 
said the Bosnian government had been in great amazement when the 
Russian Foreign Ministry asked it for explanations. "Bosnian 
planes had no need to bomb Travnik as it is an area of clashes 
between Croatians and Moslems," Churkin was quoted as saying. 
However, "whoever it was who flew above Bosnia, he violated a 
resolution of the UN Security Council and bears the entire 
responsibility for what happened," the deputy minister noted. 

</TEXT>

