<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Meets Churkin, Praises Russian Role </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802231794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2239 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802231794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 28 Feb (TANJUG) -- Following talks with 
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin this evening, 
President of the Serb Republic Radovan Karadzic stated that 
their talks focused on the continuation of efforts to restore 
peace in Bosnia. 
  At the moment it is impossible to give any more details 
since 
this process is still under way, Karadzic said. 
  The president of the Serb Republic arrived in Moscow this 
evening and immediately met Russian Deputy Foreign Minister 
Vitaliy Churkin. Their tete-a-tete meeting lasted for 45 minutes. 
  "The very fact that we are in Russia and that the Russian 
army is in our country already means a lot," Karadzic said 
following talks with Churkin. "There are a few countries in the 
world that are impartial as regards the Bosnian conflict. 
Russia is impartial in every respect, and it is also a friendly 
country,, Karadzic stressed. He went on to say that these were 
traditional relations and "an old friendship." 
  Speaking about the Russian initiative for the 
demilitarization of Sarajevo, Karadzic said that it saved the 
world many troubles. "We wish the same path to be pursued 
further. It seems to me that Russia has chosen the right way to 
contribute to the resolution of conflicts in Bosnia," Karadzic 
concluded. 
  The president of the Serb Republic is to continue talks with 
Russian officials tomorrow. He is expected to meet Russian 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev. 

</TEXT>

