<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Muslims Oppose Deployment of Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103100094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0820 
GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103100094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Sitnikov] </F>
  [Text] United Nations, 1 Mar -- Bosnian Muslims are 
against the deployment of Russian troops in Sarajevo and are 
appealing to the UN Security Council to "postpone" the 
deployment of an additional Russian contingent in Bosnia. This 
is stated in a letter from Alia Izetbegovic, the Bosnian 
president, which was forwarded to the current president of the 
UN Security Council on Monday [28 February]. This document, 
which has not been officially issued yet, was obtained by an 
Itar-Tass correspondent. 
  "The behavior of the Russian soldiers after their arrival in 
Sarajevo has annoyed UN [words indistinct] in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. Since their arrival they have displayed 
their support for the aggressor. Attitudes which remind us of 
certain episodes in the past have been strongly demonstrated. 
Our people regard this as a provocation which could cause an 
incident," Izetbegovic pointed out. 
  "We do not endorse the arrival of additional Russian forces 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina," he stressed. "We believe that any such 
decision should be put off." 

</TEXT>

