<H3> <TI>   Russia Supports UN Observers in Middle East </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802185894 Moscow Radio Moscow in Arabic 1400 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802185894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Dear listeners, the Hebron massacre that cost 
the lives of dozens of Palestinians and wounded hundreds of 
others in the al-Ibrahimi Mosque on 25 February dealt a severe 
blow to the peace process in the Middle East. It is still not 
clear who committed this crime. The Israeli Government has set 
up a committee to look into the incident. However, it is 
totally clear that the Gaza-Jericho self-rule agreements are in 
danger after a lot of effort had been put into drawing them up. 
The PLO-Israeli talks were cut on all levels. The new round of 
Arab-Israeli talks in Washington that were due to take place 
today did not start. The delegations from Syria, Lebanon, and 
Jordan decided to discuss the implications of the current 
situation first; radical Arabs are demanding revenge. Tension in 
the occupied territories has increased, but it seems doubtful 
that terrorists will succeed in torpedoing the peace proces 
because this process is extremely important. [passage omitted] 
  In 'Arafat's opinion, international forces have to be called 
in to the protect the Palestinians. Moscow believes this to be 
a good idea. Russian Foreign Minister Kozyrev stated that it 
was possible to send international observers to the area under 
UN supervision or the joint supervision of the United States and 
Russia. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

