<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks With G-7 End With Commitment to Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802194294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1649 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802194294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia and G-7 countries ended two days of talks in 
Germany on Sunday by pledging commitment to further dialogue and 
cooperation in the area of finances, a senior Finance Ministry 
official told Interfax on Monday. The Russian delegation led by 
Acting Finance Minister Sergey Dubinin was involved in the G-7 
finance ministers' meeting there. 
  The delegation also held bilateral talks with finance 
ministers of the U.S., Germany and France as well as IMF 
Managing Director Michel Camdessus and representatives of the 
Paris and London Club of donor countries, the source said. More 
importantly, he said, the G-7 countries reaffirmed their plans 
for further cooperation with Russia despite the resignation of 
Yegor Gaydar and Boris Fedorov. At the same time, it was pointed 
to the need to pay greater attention to social security matters. 
  For his part, Dubinin said that welcome as G-7 aid might be, 
Moscow would largely rely on its own resources. 
  The source said the G-7 finance ministers were invited to 
attend an EBRD-sponsored meeting in St Petersburg at the end of 
April intended to continue the dialogue. 
  On Russia-IMF talks in Moscow, the ministry official spoke 
of 
understanding reached on main issues though the two sides were 
still at odds on technicalities such as Russia's budget deficit. 
  The government plans a Rbl [rubles] 58 Tn [trillion] deficit 
this year. The Finance Ministry is ready to cover only Rbl 37 
Tn of the proposed figure at the cost of CBR credits which makes 
up about 5 percent of the GDP. Inflation will be reduced to 8-9 
percent by the end of 1994 (It ran at 22 percent in January) if 
the budget parameters are observed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

