<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aushev Wins Ingushetia Presidency by Landslide </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0103103094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 1 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK0103103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Natalya Gorodetskaya report under the "North Caucasus" </F>
rubric: "Ruslan Aushev Is Ingushetia President by Wide Margin, 
According to Preliminary Data"] 
  [Text] Elections for president and parliament, and a 
referendum on the republic's draft constitution were held in 
Nazran on 27 February. Despite Moscow's indifference to the 
elections and referendum in Ingushetia and the fact that it 
provided no money from the budget to pay for them, the required 
billion rubles, according to Batyr Taldiyev, chairman of the 
republican district electoral commission, had been found in the 
republic's coffers. 
  Seventy-five polling stations opened at 0800 that Sunday 
morning where 105,000 voters (without taking into account the 
Ingush people who came from North Ossetia during the 
Ossetia-Ingushetia armed conflict) came to express their will. 
  The Ingushetia presidency was contested by current President 
Ruslan Aushev and Bamatgirey Mankiyev, a former state farm 
director. According to preliminary data, Ruslan Aushev won by a 
landslide. This had not been doubted in principle if one thinks 
about the small artillery preparation for the presidential 
elections two weeks ago in which Ruslan Aushev declined to run 
for the presidency, saying that his motive was his unwillingness 
"to bear responsibility for a repeat escalation of tensions 
owing to the ineptness of some politicians," because, in his 
view, "the current policy would lead to a new flare-up of the 
Ossetia-Ingushetia conflict this April or May." The Ingush 
president has lately been sharply critical of the Russian 
Federation temporary administration in the Ossetia-Ingushetia 
conflict zone because, he thinks, it puts the brakes on the 
implementation of Boris Yeltsin's edict on a phased return of 
Ingush refugees to four population centers of North Ossetia's 
Prigorodnyy Rayon. In the wake of the president's dramatic 
statement, the majority of eligible Ingush voters unanimously 
decided, as a snap poll showed, that Ruslan Aushev "cannot be 
excused from the president's post, and he cannot go against the 
will of the people." He collected 70,000 votes in his support. 
  Ruslan Aushev voted yesterday for the republic's draft 
constitution and for 27 deputies for parliament. Mr. Aushev did 
not vote for president and vice president, thinking that "voting 
for himself is unethical." 
  The new president is to meet soon with the head of North 
Ossetia. The question of a possible meeting had already been 
taken up at the experts level. True, negotiations about the 
return of Ingush refugees to North Ossetia's Prigorodnyy Rayon 
would hardly be a simple matter because North Ossetia President 
Akhsarbek Galazov, who had the idea for the meeting, stated that 
the problem of normalization of relations between the republics 
is being forced into a blind alley in which one of the sides 
(implying the North Ossetia side) is being pressured. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-14880 </DOCNO>
