<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Service Chief Views Trial </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802201294 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1428 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev--The trial of Major Anatoliy Lysenko, a staff 
member of the Mostiska customs house of the Security Service of 
Ukraine [SBU], continued in Warsaw on 28 February. Lysenko is 
accused of espionage. The prosecutor is demanding a five-year 
prison sentence for Lysenko. 
  Asked by a UNIAN correspondent to comment on the "Lysenko 
case", SBU Chairman Yevhen Marchuk said: "We have been trying 
for a long time now not to make any comment at all on this 
regrettable incident in mutual relations between our two 
neighboring, friendly states. I would like to say only that SBU 
Major Anatoliy Lysenko has nothing to do with our intelligence. 
He had no mission and went to Poland with his wife and children 
to attend to personal matters. The only thing that he may be 
rebuked for is that he went abroad without having waited for the 
SBU leadership's consent, thus acting in breach of service 
discipline. Our view is that the Polish special services' 
actions with respect to Lysenko were instigated by someone else: 
There probably are certain forces in Poland that do not want 
rapprochement between our friendly people. Nevertheless, we 
hope common sense will prevail". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

