<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Press Service Interprets Kravchuk Statement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2802165894 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 25 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2802165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Undated "Statement by the Ukrainian Presidential and </F>
Cabinet of Ministers Press Service"] 
  [Text] During a meeting with representatives of the mass 
media organized at the request of Radio "Liberty" and the 
[German] magazine DER SPIEGEL, Ukrainian President Leonid 
Kravchuk, briefing the journalists on the political situation in 
Ukraine in connection with the forthcoming elections to power 
structures at all levels, said that he considered his 
participation in the early presidential elections set for 26 
June 1994 inexpedient. 
  President Leonid Kravchuk justified his idea by the 
insufficient time for holding elections at all levels. It 
cannot be ruled out that the process of election and formation 
of supreme bodies of legislative and executive power may go 
beyond the time assigned for it and may overlap the course of 
early presidential elections and elections to local organs of 
power. This may lead to a vacuum of power, when the old Supreme 
Council is no more, a new one is not yet in existence, and 
Ukraine's Supreme Council, which might take upon itself the 
entire executive power, has not yet been formed. In this 
situation, the president alone may actually fulfill state 
functions. If he also participates in elections at that time, 
executive structures may collapse and control may be totally 
lost. This is the determining argument. 
  In view of the fact that the idea expressed in the 
aforementioned interview is being ambiguously commented upon 
both in Ukraine and abroad, the Ukrainian Presidential and 
Cabinet of Ministers Press Service points out that the position 
expressed by Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk was due to 
precisely that specific situation in the life of our society and 
state that took shape today and to its possible development in 
the near future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-14889 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov040_f_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-040 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

