<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Official Opposes Separate Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103121394 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 25 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "A Meeting of the Crimean Supreme </F>
Council Presidium"] 
  [Text] The Crimean Supreme Council Presidium has held a 
meeting. Opening it, speaker of the Crimean parliament Nikolay 
Bagrov said that the situation on the peninsula is complex and 
that "we need to create normal conditions for the president's 
work." Bagrov negatively assessed Ukraine's Supreme Council's 
decision to hold elections to local state authorities on 26 
June, the same date as the [Ukrainian] presidential elections. 
Bagrov proposed that this question be raised at the session of 
the Crimean parliament. The proposal by Viktor Bobylev, a member 
of the Presidium, that the moratorium on holding a referendum on 
the Crimean Republic's independence be lifted did not meet with 
support. 
  The Crimean parliament's speaker touched upon the discussion 
at the session of the question of forming the Crimean Republic's 
budget. "If, today, the city [as published] must receive an 
income of 700 billion karbovantsi, the question of the budget 
will not be at all simple," Bagrov pointed out. "I very much 
fear that once Ukraine has given us the chance to form our own 
budget independently and does not give us anything, we will not 
be able to survive." 
  Asked by journalists whether the Crimea will be able to 
become a subject of international law, Bagrov replied: "This 
topic must be removed from the agenda. Economic relations are 
one thing, but political relations are something entirely 
different." 
  Crimean President Yuriy Meshkov took part in the work of the 
Crimean Supreme Council Presidium. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

