<H3> <TI>   Minister Says Armenians Accept Cease-Fire Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0103095594 Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 2050 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0103095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 2050 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Armenian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Talks were held in Yerevan on 28 February between 
Davit Shahnazaryan, the Armenian president's ambassador on 
special missions and acting head of the State Directorate for 
National Security; Armenian Defense Minister Serzh Sargisyan; 
the Russian president's representative in the region, Validimir 
Kazimirov; and the Russian Deputy Defense Minister Georgiy 
Kondratyev on finalizing the cease-fire agreement concluded 
during the meeting of the defense ministers of Armenia, 
Azerbaijan, and Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  Kondratyev assessed the talks: I faced no problems in 
Armenia. The Armenian side, Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh, agrees 
to fully implement the Moscow agreement and cease fire as of 1 
March. I am leaving for Baku today. I hope to receive a 
similar reply there. It could be stated that a first step 
leading to peace is being taken. Russia, Kondratyev noted, will 
terminate its mediatory mission if Azerbaijan refuses to 
implement or disagrees with any of the provisions of the 
agreement. After all, both the Armenians and the Azerbaijanis 
are longing for the war to end. 
  He also noted that the planned visit to Stepanakert was not 
possible due to weather conditions. But the deputy defense 
minister assured that he will be there at the first opportunity. 

</TEXT>

