<H3> <TI>   President Denies NATO To Have Bases in Republic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602220294 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1930 GMT 
26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2602220294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Radio Slavyanka" program of the Russsian Defense </F>
Ministry] 
  [Text] Radio Slavyanka has reported, quoting the VECHERNIY 
BISHKEK newspaper, that Kyrgyzstan's leadership is holding talks 
with NATO on providing the bloc with military bases on the 
territory of the republic. The newspaper wrote that when its 
correspondent approached the Kyrgyzstan Defense Ministry for an 
explanation, it was unable to either confirm or deny this 
report. During his official visit to Moscow, the republican 
President Askar Akayev clarified the situation in an interview 
with our correspondent. 
  [Begin Akayev recording] This will never happen, because we 
were one of the first co-founders of the collective security 
council. We were one of the first five countries in Tashkent to 
sign the collective security treaty and the decision to set up 
joint CIS Armed Forces. So of course we will rely on the joint 
armed forces in the business of defending our security and 
ensuring peace in Kyrgyzstan, and indeed in all the countries of 
the CIS, on the territory of the whole of the former USSR. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

