<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ostankino TV Programming Facing Cuts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802162994 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1500 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802162994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Correspondent Vladimir Fedorov report from Kyrgyzstan; from </F>
the "Novosti" newscast] 
  [Text] It is hard to assess the new schedule for broadcasts 
by Kyrgyz State Television as anything other than a stab in the 
back for the republic's president. From today, Ostankino 
broadcasts are being removed here after the newscast at 2100 
local time. Almaty and Tashkent programs, previously carried on 
another channel alongside Turkish broadcasts, are replacing 
them. Now, Ankara broadcasts solidly between 0900 and 0200 the 
next morning in a language that is completely unintelligible to 
the overwhelming majority of the Kyrgyz population. 
  It is, however, intelligible to local television and 
communication officials. Ostankino is in arrears for some 
reason, whereas the Turks pay up and have even handed over 
written-off video cameras as gifts. 
  It is typical that the squeezing out of Russian programs - 
and Mayak has also been subject to this policy - has occurred 
during the absence of Askar Akayev, who is now on vacation in 
Barvikha outside Moscow following his successful talks with 
Boris Yeltsin on the receipt of 75 billion rubles for a program 
to prevent the migration of Russians in Kyrgyzstan and to 
preserve the use of the Russian language. 
  As a result of this new assault on Ostankino, the republic's 
viewers will this week lose their evening news bulletins on 
Thursday and Saturday and also the "Voskresenye" program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

