<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ioseliani Says UN Troops To Be Sent to Abkhazia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802123194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1137 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802123194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The chief Georgian negotiator at the 
Georgian-Abkhazian talks in Geneva, Jaba Ioseliani, has said 
that "UN troops will be deployed in Abkhazia, whether the 
Gugauta grouping wants it or not, and the process of refugees' 
return will begin." "This is what the Gudauta leaders are afraid 
of, since in this case all their claims to statehood will be 
buried," he told journalists in Tbilisi. 
  The Abkhazian leadership stands for deploying peacekeeping 
forces on the border between Abkhazia and Georgia along the 
River Inguri. 
  In comments on the results of the 3rd round of talks held on 
February 22nd-25th, Ioseliani said that the Georgian delegation 
knew from the outset that "the Abkhazian side will not accept 
any constructive solutions." "Nevertheless we met with them, so 
that the entire world can see with whom we are dealing," he said. 
  According to Ioseliani, all participants in the talks "were 
indignant at the destructive stance taken by Gudauta." 
Discussions on the Abkhazian problem are continuing at the U.N. 
in New York, he noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

