<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin To Seek Common Ground With Duma Chairman </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802192394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1857 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 28 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin will meet with his senior aides and the State Duma 
chairman on Tuesday to discuss ways to boost cooperation between 
the legislative and executive branches, Yeltsin's Chief of Staff 
Sergey Filatov said on Monday. 
  The statement was made after his meeting with Duma Chairman 
Ivan Rybkin, following the State Duma decision on amnesty for 
the leaders of the 1991 August failed coup, May Day riots and 
the October 1993 revolt in Moscow. 
  Filatov said that the recent events have revealed the lack 
of 
proper interaction between the two branches. He noted that both 
sides will set up working groups to iron out disagreements 
before March 10 when the Duma, the lower house, will reconvene. 
However, he refused to say in what particular directions the 
groups will be working, adding that the State Duma, as a 
collegiate body, should first "hold an internal discussion of 
what has happened." 
  Speaking about reports that Yeltsin was planning to address 
the nation on television tonight, Filatov said he did not know 
anything about it. 
  "It is most important to understand that the Duma's 
resolution means amnesty for only some people, but the 
investigation should be carried on," Filatov said. 
  The meeting was also attended by Acting Public Prosecutor 
Aleksey Ilyushenko, Yeltsin's representative in the State Duma 
Aleksandr Yakovlev and his senior aide Georgiy Satarov. 

</TEXT>

