<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Says Amnesty Applies to 20,000 Prisoners </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2802164594 Moscow PRAVDA in Russian 26 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2802164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report: "Amnesty No Danger to Society"] </F>
  [Text] An insignificant number of convicts, approximately 
20,000 out of the more than 800,000 held in corrective labor 
camps and solitary confinement centers, will be released from 
their places of confinement. Major General of the Interior 
Service Valeriy Orlov, first deputy chief of the Russian 
Interior Ministry's Main Directorate for Enforcing Sentences, 
said this in conversation with an ITAR-TASS correspondent 
yesterday. 
  He noted that, formally speaking, the amnesty covers a far 
greater number of people and this has given rise to various 
conjectures and rumor. However, the present amnesty will not be 
anything like the general release of recidivists well known from 
the movie "The cold summer of 1953." In the main the people to 
be released will be the very old, whom it is simply inhuman to 
keep in places of deprivation of liberty, invalids, and minors, 
as well as first-time offenders guilty of a crime of negligence 
or of a crime which does not pose an exaggerated danger to 
society. In particular, those who took part in combat actions 
in defense of the motherland will be freed from punishment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

