<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Amnesty, Release of Prisoners </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kozyrev Urges Return to Prison </H4>
<F P=102> LD2802180594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1655 
GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Georgiy Shmelev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 28 Feb -- Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev is convinced that neither the decision to amnesty 
Rutskoy, Khasbulatov, and their associates, nor these people 
themselves "can in any measure destabilize the situation in the 
country, which is guaranteed by the provisions of the 
constitution and the policy of the Russian president." 
  Speaking today at a regular meeting with Russian and foreign 
journalists at the Foreign Ministry of the Russian Federation, 
Andrey Kozyrev, who is a deputy, also said that for him and many 
other Russian parliamentarians the Duma's decision on a 
political amnesty "seems shameful." "These people," he stated, 
"should be in prison. They broke the law and should be sent 
back to prison and tried. And then, perhaps, an amnesty will be 
extended to them." 
  This is a "mistake by those who released them," the minister 
stressed, "and I think the Russian president will take the 
appropriate decision in his own time." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

