<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Amnesty, Release of Prisoners </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sobchak: Amnesty Challenge to Yeltsin </H4>
<F P=102> LD0103092594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2305 
GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103092594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Fomicheva] </F>
  [Text] St. Petersburg, 1 Mar -- St. Petersburg Mayor 
Anatoliy Sobchak called the amnesty a human act, commenting at 
the request of an ITAR-TASS correspondent on the amnesty for the 
Lefortovo detainees declared by the State Duma. But he said 
that "this decision is an act of political struggle and a 
challenge to the president and to the policy he is conducting. 
It cannot fail to act as a means of political destabilization." 
  In Sobchak's view, "the point is not that people should be 
in 
prison; the main thing is that the actual crime should be 
condemned. 
  "There is no doubt that a crime was committed on 3-4 October 
last year against the individual and the state, an armed 
rebellion that led to numerous fatalities. That fact cannot be 
erased by any amnesties at all." 
  Anatoliy Sobchak recalled that the first draft constitution 
stated that an amnesty could be declared by the Federal 
Assembly, i.e. the State Duma and the Federation Council. 
Unfortunately, he said, in the final version of the 
Constitution, that stipulation fell by the wayside, and only the 
State Duma retained the right, which the opposition took 
advantage of. 
  Nevertheless, St. Petersburg's mayor stressed, the State 
Duma 
had the right to declare an amnesty, and there are only a number 
of questions connected with the wording of the amnesty 
declaration. "It's one thing when it covers people who are 
involved in mass disorders; it's quite another thing when they 
are involved in violence and murder. That is precisely the 
charge brought against a whole string of participants in the 
events of October." 
  According to Sobchak, an actual amnesty can be applied only 
to persons who are guilty of committing crimes. "But if they do 
not acknowledge their guilt, an amnesty cannot apply to them." 
This legal problem should have been resolved by the 
Procurator-General's office before the organizers of the October 
rebellion were released." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

