<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy Denies War Propaganda Charges </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103115994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1125 
GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS correspondent Roman Zadunayskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 1 March -- Vladimir Zhirinovskiy has totally 
denied all accusations of propagandizing war during questioning 
by a military procurator. On Monday evening he was questioned 
by a procurator of the Main Military Procuracy, which is 
conducting the Zhirinovskiy case. The LDPR [Liberal Democratic 
Party of Russia] leader denied that his book, "The Last Dash 
South," and other printed or verbal speeches called for war, 
combat actions, and the annexation of other states to Russia. 
  Earlier, on 25 February, Irina Kulikova, vice president of 
the Aesthetics Association of the Russian Academy of Sciences, 
was summoned to the Main Military Procuracy for questioning. 
She is the author of a book on the LDPR leader, "The 
Zhirinovskiy Phenomenon," assisted in putting together "The Last 
Dash South," and, in the opinion of observers, is a spiritual 
mentor of Vladimir Volfovich. Irina Kulikova also denied that 
in "The Last Dash South" or other printed or verbal speeches 
Zhirinovskiy had called for war or violence. 
  It was earlier reported that a criminal case had been 
instituted under Article 71 of the Russian Criminal Code, 
"Propagandizing war in any form," against Vladimir Zhirinovskiy 
by the Procurator General's office after numerous requests from 
citizens were made to law enforcement bodies and the Central 
Electoral Commission in connection with their having seen calls 
for war in publications and speeches by the LDPR leader. The 
Main Military Procuracy has been charged with conducting the 
Zhirinovskiy case. 

</TEXT>

