<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Funding Threatens Broadcasts in Former Republics </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502191394 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1400 GMT 
25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502191394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian radio and television broadcasts in the near 
abroad could be halted soon, because in practice no funds are 
being allocated from the Russian budget for this purpose. A RIA 
correspondent was told this by Sergey Yerofeyev, director for 
international links at the All-Russian State Television and 
Radio Company. He said that in line with existing global 
practice, a country or a specific television and radio station 
broadcasting a program within its territory from another state 
must not only itself accept the expenditure involved, but often 
also pay considerable money for the right to relay these 
programs. In the territories of the former Union everything is 
the other way around. 
  Except for Turkmenistan, Belarus, and certain other CIS 
countries, which have assumed responsibility for the expenditure 
involved, the other states are producing uncertainty by their 
statements that they cannot pay for the reception of Russian 
television and radio broadcasts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

