<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   TV Reports 73 Percent Vote in Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802144694 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1200 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Approximately 50 percent [figure as heard] of voters 
in Moldova voted in the pre-term parliamentary elections for the 
Agrarian Democratic Party [ADP]. Those running on the ADP list 
included Petr Lucinschi, the speaker of the present parliament, 
and Andrey Sangeli, the prime minister. In all, 73 percent of 
Moldovans took part in the elections. 
  Parties of leftwing orientation, running in the Socialist 
Party-Movement For Equal Rights and Unity bloc, scored an 
unexpected success, gaining 23 percent of the vote. The Popular 
Christian Democratic Front and the bloc of peasants and 
intellectuals, whose main aim is unification with Romania, 
gained approximately 14 percent of the votes. In fourth place, 
according to as yet preliminary figures, was the Social 
Democratic Party, which received 13 percent of the votes. 
  Political specialists in Moldova believe that a constructive 
majority will be formed in the new parliament which will favor 
the further strengthening of Moldovan statehood - in particular, 
the implementation of a balanced foreign policy - and closer 
economic integration with all republics of the Commonwealth. 

</TEXT>

