<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   CIS Officers Transfer to Russian Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK2502092094 Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS in Russian 25 Feb 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK2502092094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Enemy Troops Go Over to the Russian </F>
Side Without a Single Shot"] 
  [Text] MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS has learned form reliable 
sources that the officer corps of the Russian Armed Forces grew 
by 3,000 men in 1993 at the expense of the Armed Forces of CIS 
countries. 
  Officers from these armies leave the service to sign up 
immediately with the Russian Armed Forces. For instance, over 
1,000 officers deserted the Kazakhstani Army for the Russian 
one; from Belarus, 800 officers; and from Ukraine, 1,000. For 
the most part, these are Air Force pilots and Missile Troops 
servicemen. They have been lured into the Russian Army by 
higher wages. 
  It is expected that this year the flow of deserters, 
particularly from Kazakhstan, will grow, not drop. In 
Kazakhstan, they have started levying income taxes on servicemen 
and stripped them of some of their former benefits. 

</TEXT>

