<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 2 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0203110894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0644 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0203110894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press Review" -- ITAR-TASS headline] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 2 TASS -- PRAVDA runs a statement by 
former Russian Prosecutor-General Aleksey Kazannik, who, in 
explanation of his resignation, maintains that he was 
pressurised on the part of President Boris Yeltsin, since a 
message from Baturin, assistant to the president on state 
security, suggested that "the act of amnesty be not enacted or 
be at least dragged out". In this connection Kazannik 
emphasises that "the prosecutor's office has not right to 
legislative initiative. It does not discuss acts but accurately 
and undeviatingly applies normative-legal acts". 
  ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI reports that "upon release, Russia's 
former 
Vice-President Aleksandr Rutskoy applied to former parliament 
speaker Ruslan Khasbulatov in a proposal to convene an 
extraordinary congress of the people's deputies of Russia. This 
was announced on Tuesday by presidential chief of staff Sergey 
Filatov when he was introducing Aleksey Ilyushenko to the staff 
of the office of the prosecutor-general. Ilyushenko was 
appointed acting prosecutor- general of the Russian Federation 
by a presidential decree." 
  ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI on recent developments: "The events of the 
recent days have shown once again the weakness of state power, 
the need to strengthen which was mentioned by the president in 
his message to the Federal Assembly. Not just the weakness of 
all its elements but complete mismatch in their functioning. 
  "It has turned out that we have got a not so strong 
constitution if the need for its interpretation arose when it 
was necessary to take a serious decision" 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA on the crisis of power in Moscow: 
  "All maintain that the current crisis of power in Moscow has 
been provoked by the State Duma's well-known decision on a 
political amnesty. However, it is now clear that the crisis was 
triggered by no means by the Duma decision but by the attitude 
of former Prosecutor-General Aleksey Kazannik (and, apparently, 
that of former chief of the Federal Counterintelligence Service 
Nikolay Golushko). 
  "Presidential assistants' incoherent reasoning, because of 
which they are blamed for lack of professionalism and 
efficiency, proves not the lack of the assistants' 
professionalism but the non- professinalism of the order issued 
to them -- to give explanations at a press conference. How can 
they give explanations when Kazannik is backed by law and they 
are backed only by their boss's instruction?" 
  KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA carries an interview with State Duma 
speaker Ivan Rybkin, who expresses his opinion about the 
announced amnesty. He said "the amnesty is intended for a 
sufficiently long period of time. According to the president's 
legislative initiative, a total of 222,000 people are to be 
released from places of confinement, plus those who were 
involved in the events of the August of 1991, May, September and 
October 1993. 
  "It so happened that due to insufficiently efficient 
interaction of authorities, there was a certain inconsistency in 
the realisation of the decisions taken. All this undoubtedly 
brings about certain problems in society," Rybkin said. 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA runs an article by Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev. 
  "It has long become clear that in present-day conditions an 
aggressive nationalism, the Brezhnev and 'Berlin Wall' 
doctrines, domination ambitions, and 'sanitary cordones' are 
unacceptable," he writes. 
  "It is now essential to ensure stability and security for 
the 
entire Europe and jointly overcome ethnic conflicts... it is 
important now not to lose the positive movement momentum created 
by Presdient Boris Yeltsin's initiative which led to a major 
breakthrough in lifting the siege of Sarajevo. 
  "Energetic and joint actions are necessary. Individual 
powers and their associations, including NATO, will find their 
place and make their contributions within the context of 
combined efforts". 
  VECHERNYY PETERBURG reports that the assembly of lower 
panels 
in the Amber Room of the Catherine Palace in Tsarskoye Selo is 
nearing completion. Over the past nine years local restorers 
have made anew almost 40 percent of panels. 
  The main restoring work will apparently have to be suspended 
because not a single gramme of amber has come from Kaliningrad 
over a period of almost three years. All amber is exported from 
there at commercial prices. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

