<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur on New Constitution, CIS </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103141394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1106 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0103141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moldovan President Mircea Snegur has told INTERFAX 
that the country's newly-elected parliament is to consider and 
approve a new constitution which must secure the republic's 
independence and its development along the road of consolidation 
and strengthening of contacts with all countries. 
  "We can only regret about the breaking up of ties on the 
economic space of the former Soviet Union," he said. 
  Snegur believes that Moldova is unable to reject the Eastern 
market. 
  "We have had a try of following the agreements at 
Belovezhskaya Pushcha. As a result our economic indices have 
dropped very low," said Snegur. 
  He sees the way out of the situation in implemeting the 
agreement on the formation of an economic union within the 
framework of the Commonwealth of Independent States, which was 
signed by Moldova. 
  Snegur has denied speculation saying that Moldova intends to 
sign, within the CIS, agreements other than economic. 
  "We take part in integration on the issues that do not 
infringe our independence," he said. 
  Speaking about the relationships with Romania, he said: "We 
have one language, we are brothers and continue integrating 
economically and culturally, but we are building our independent 
states." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

