<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   European Observers `Satisfied' With Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103163494 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 1840 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103163494 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau, BASAPRESS, 28/2/1994 -- The Council of 
Europe Observation Group is satisfied with the way in which 
elections in Moldovan Parliament were organized and held, 
declared the delegation chief Lambert Kelchtermaans at a 
press-conference today. Though some infringements were 
detected, they were unlikely to influence the results of first 
democratic elections based on pluripartisism. The delegation 
chief mentioned that the observation group visited over 40 
voting sections. According to the collected information 
analyzed by the Council of Europe delegation a final report will 
be presented to the Bureau of the Assembly of the 32. This 
report will be the basic element in the adherence of Moldova to 
the Council of Europe, which Council experts think will last for 
a longer period. Before the conference Parliament Speaker Petru 
Lucinschi assured the foreign observers that Moldova will cause 
no trouble to Europe" and wishes to join Europe with a 
democratic system and market economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

