<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Observers on Results </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103164094 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 1840 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103164094 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau, BASAPRESS, 28/2/1994 -- Electoral 
observers from NATO and CSCE held today a press conference. The 
first pluripartite democratic elections in Moldova were run in 
"an atmosphere of normality and honesty" and according to the 
law on elections to parliament, stated from behalf of NATO 
delegation. The observers visited over 60 polling stations in 
various Moldova's regions; they noticed some technical and 
organization deficiencies, mainly caused by the lack of 
democratic experience in Moldova and this is not a reason to 
contest the results, says a press release issued by the 
observers. Lord Lucas said that about 12 percent of left bank 
population voted while other inhabitants of east Moldova had, 
though with difficulties, the real possibility to participate in 
elections. NATO and CSCE observers remarked as "a suggestion 
for future" the state's obligation to insure equal access to 
media for all political forces during the electoral campaign. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

