<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   CIS Troops To Remain Until Dec 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802151794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1430 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802151794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 28 TASS -- CIS peace-keeping forces 
will stay in Tajikistan until December 31, 1994, Viktor 
Samsonov, chief coordinator of CIS military cooperation, said. 
  Speaking at a news conference in Moscow on Monday, Samsonov 
said that the troops will be reinforced by additional 
contingents of CIS states which are providing peace-keeping 
assistance to the republic under inter-state agreements. 
  The decision to this effect was adopted by the CIS defence 
ministers at their two-day meeting in Moscow last week. 
  Samsonov stressed that the decision on measures to stabilise 
the situation on the Tajik-Afghan border adopted by the defence 
ministers will be transformed into a law at the upcoming session 
of the CIS heads of state. 
  Under the existing agreements, Kyrgyzstan will reinforce its 
contingent in Tajikistan and Kazakhstan will send in a battalion 
in the near future. 
  If Afghan mujahideen and the Tajik opposition launch a 
large-scale offensive on the border in the spring or summer, 
"the available peace-keeping troops will not be enough to repel 
it," Samsonov said. 
  Asked about disagreements between the military delegations 
of 
CIS states, Samsonov said that the decision on the stabilisation 
of the situation on the Tajik-Afghan border was signed by all 
delegations, except Belarus. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

