<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Discusses Future of Nuclear Power </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103140094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1106 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0103140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk believes that 
"today, atomic power plants can save Ukraine." He declared 
about this at a meeting with heads of the republic's atomic 
power plants on Monday. 
  The president reassured that the problem related to the 
supply of atomic plants with fuel would be solved in the near 
term, and in accordance with the tripartite statement between 
Ukraine, Russia, and United States signed in Moscow. Russia 
pledged to deliver fuel for atomic power plants in exchange for 
nuclear warheads. 
  In Kravchuk's words, currently, the government is solving 
issues to improve material conditions for the employees of 
atomic stations. In particular, the income tax for key experts 
of atomic power stations is to be lowered by 10%. 
  Kravchuk said that the proposal of atomic power stations' 
leaders to introduce world prices for power supply should be 
thoroughly examined. He said that "one should do this very 
accurately and in a balanced manner so as not to deepen the 
crisis phenomena in the economy and in the state." In 
Kravchuk's opinion, the issue of drawing foreign investments 
into atomic energy "is to be further analyzed and examined." 
  A presidential decree on urgent measures to develop the 
atomic energy complex is expected to be issued in the near 
future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

