<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Vice Premier `Cautious' on Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203104894 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 26 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0203104894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "The Crimean Vice Premier: There </F>
Will Be No Miracle"] 
  [Text] Yevgeniy Saburov, invited by the Crimean president 
to occupy the post of vice premier, began to study the 
situation. He is a candidate of economic sciences, full member 
of the Russian Information Science Academy and of the Russian 
Academy of Social Sciences. He is 47, was born and grew up in 
Yalta [Crimea]. In a conversation with journalists, he said 
that he has his own "team," but is not yet going to change the 
people in the present Crimean government -- he will first look 
closely at them. He said that there would be no miracle: The 
Crimea cannot become happy over two days on such a basis as two 
inflating currencies and severed economic ties. As regards the 
introduction into circulation of the Russian ruble, an economic 
union with Russia, Ukraine, and other no less important matters, 
Ye. Saburov was very cautious in his statements and gave to 
understand that he does not want any tension in the relations 
between these states and is going to act exclusively proceeding 
from interstate agreements. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

