<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nazarbayev Says Russia `Priority Partner' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0103143794 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 26 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM0103143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Anatoliy Ladin report: "Russia and Kazakhstan Remain </F>
Partners. Nursultan Nazarbayev Defended Russia During His 
Recent Visit to America"] 
  [Text] Almaty -- At a news conference held in Almaty, 
Nursultan Nazarbayev returned several times to the subject of 
his personal attitude toward Kazakhstani-Russian ties. In his 
opinion, relations between the two states are developing 
normally at present, and no actions aimed at infringing Russian 
interests were undertaken during his visit to the United States. 
  The president of Kazakhstan confirmed that during his U.S. 
visit, many people asked about the situation in Russia. He 
tried to convince his partners in the talks that they should 
gamble not on the specific persons carrying out the economic 
reforms in Russia but on the actual process of democratic and 
economic transformations. He raised objections with those 
interlocutors in America who called the Chernomyrdin government 
conservative; according to Nazarbayev, he was able to 
demonstrate why he disagreed by using as a basis his own 
personal experience of relations with the Russian head of 
government. 
  The president illumined in detail the problem connected with 
the upcoming removal of the nuclear warheads of strategic 
missiles from Kazakhstani territory. 
  Kazakhstan is claiming 10 percent of the estimated value of 
all the uranium of the missiles which are on the territory of 
four CIS states and which are subject to reduction. 
  On the whole, Nursultan Nazarbayev advocated lending 
viability to the CIS states' economic union as quickly as 
possible. He said that Russia remains Kazakhstan's priority 
partner. At the same it must be taken into account that "it 
takes two to tango," the president emphasized figuratively. 
Therefore the desire for cooperation must be mutual. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

