<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rutskoy Accepts Legitimacy of New Legislature </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0203120594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0836 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0203120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow March 2 ITAR-TASS -- Former Vice-President 
Aleksandr Rutskoy, proclaimed Russia's president last autumn by 
Ruslan Khasbulatov's parliament already proclaimed dismissed by 
Yeltsin, said a couple of days after his release from jail last 
week that he accepts the legitimacy of the legislature Yeltsin 
created in the former parliament's place. This new legislature 
ruled on an amnesty which freed Rutskoy, Khasbulatov and other 
organisers of armed resistance to Yeltsin's move to crush the 
old Soviet-era parliament last October. 
  Rutskoy called for a spirit of reconciliation in Russia in a 
statement faxed to Russian and foreign news agencies on 
Wednesday. In the same statement he defended the armed 
resistance to Yeltsin's move last autumn. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

