<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Press Service Says No TV Address Planned </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0203080094 Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS in Russian 2 Mar 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK0203080094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Mikhail Gurevich report: "Don't Believe Anyone But </F>
President's Press Service and President Himself"] 
  [Text] The persistent speculation in the press about 
Yeltsin's television appearance still remains only speculation. 
It was not planned either for 28 February or 1 March (this 
information was available to MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS from the 
president's press service as this issue was going to print). 
The rumor about the appearance must have been raised by 
journalists' speculation which presidential aides Baturin and 
Satarov did not wish to deny, stating that it was "not far from 
the truth." In principle, the above aides could have said 
nothing at all because, as Yeltsin's press service officers 
stated to MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS, all official communiques about 
Yeltsin's addresses are supposed to come from it. Well, and -- 
certainly -- from the president himself. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

